## A. Propagation of Energy Measurement Uncertainty

Given an initial photon energy $E_{\text {init }}$ and a deposited photon energy $E_{1}$ at first interaction. The Compton scattering equation in terms of the deposited photon energy is given by 1 . To find the uncertainty in the scattering angle $\theta_{\mathrm{C}}$ due to the uncertainty
in the measured energy, we first take the derivative of $\cos \left(\theta_{\mathrm{C}}\right)$ with respect to $E_{1}$ :

$$
\frac{\mathrm{d}\left(\cos \left(\theta_{\mathrm{C}}\right)\right)}{\mathrm{d} E_{1}}=-\frac{m_{\mathrm{e}} c^{2}}{\left(E_{\text {init }}-E_{1}\right)^{2}}
$$

The uncertainty in $\cos \left(\theta_{\mathrm{C}}\right)$ is then given by:

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta \cos \left(\theta_{\mathrm{C}, \text { energy }}\right) & =\left|\frac{\mathrm{d}\left(\cos \left(\theta_{\mathrm{C}}\right)\right)}{\mathrm{d} E_{1}}\right| \Delta E_{1} \\
& =\left|\frac{m_{\mathrm{e}} c^{2}}{\left(E_{\text {init }}-E_{1}\right)^{2}}\right| \Delta E_{1}
\end{aligned}
$$

Finally, we convert this to the uncertainty in $\theta_{\mathrm{C}}$ :

$$
\begin{aligned}
\Delta \theta_{\mathrm{C}, \text { energy }} & =\frac{\Delta \cos \left(\theta_{\mathrm{C}, \text { mes }}\right)}{\sin \left(\theta_{\mathrm{C}}\right)} \\
& =\frac{\left|-\frac{m_{\mathrm{e}} c^{2}}{\left(E_{\text {init }}-E_{1}\right)^{2}}\right| \Delta E_{1}}{\sin \left(\theta_{\mathrm{C}}\right)}
\end{aligned}
$$

This equation shows how the error in the measured photon energy propagates to the uncertainty in the scattering angle.
